The '''encapsulins''' are a family of bacterial proteins that serve as the main structural components of [[encapsulin nanocompartment]]s.<ref name="McHugh 2014">{{cite journal | vauthors = McHugh CA, Fontana J, Nemecek D, Cheng N, Aksyuk AA, Heymann JB, Winkler DC, Lam AS, Wall JS, Steven AC, Hoiczyk E | title = A virus capsid-like nanocompartment that stores iron and protects bacteria from oxidative stress | journal = The EMBO Journal | volume = 33 | issue = 17 | pages = 1896–911 | date = September 2014 | pmid = 25024436 | pmc = 4195785 | doi = 10.15252/embj.201488566 }}</ref> There are several different encapsulin proteins, including EncA, which forms the shell, and EncB, EncC, and EncD, which form the core.<ref name="McHugh 2014"/>
